The paper proposes a framework for privacy-preserving machine learning, which suggests that it could belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) category. The framework is motivated by the desire to achieve differential privacy guarantees, which suggests that it could also belong to the cryptography and security (cs.CR) category. The framework relies on random sampling of models for load distribution, which suggests that it could belong to the data structures (cs.DS) category. The paper also mentions the use of Generalized Linear models, which suggests that it could belong to the databases (cs.DB) category. Finally, the paper presents experimental results that provide evidence for the framework's viability in practical deployments, which suggests that it could belong to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) category.
